    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Ok, I think I at least understand the problem(s).\r\n\r\nFirst up:\r\n\r\n```\r\n2023-09-18 11:06:44.982 [debu]  net.tailnet.net.wgengine: magicsock: last netcheck reported send error. Rebinding.\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis happens because netcheck is supposed to verify that we can send a UDP packet to at least one STUN server.  Since we disable all STUN servers when we disable P2P, netcheck always fails this test. Tailscale thinks that we can't send any IPv4 packets and should rebind our sockets, I guess because the usual reason you can't send UDP packets is that you're bound to the wrong interface (e.g. Wifi getting turned on & off, VM getting network interfaces connected and disconnected).\r\n\r\nNext up,\r\n\r\n```\r\n2023-09-18 11:06:44.983 [debu]  net.tailnet.net.wgengine: Rebind; defIf=\\\"eth0\\\", ips=[192.168.100.148/24 fe80::5054:ff:fee8:4244/64]\r\n\"2023-09-18 11:06:44.983 [debu]  net.tailnet.net.wgengine: magicsock: closing connection to derp-999 (rebind-default-route-change), age 1s\r\n\"2023-09-18 11:06:44.983 [debu]  net.tailnet.net.wgengine: magicsock: 0 active derp conns\r\n```\r\n\r\nWhile rebinding, tailscale checks whether the DERP connections local address match the address(es) it discovered for the preferred interface.  In most sane real systems, the outgoing DERP connection should use an outgoing interface.  But, in our tests, DERP uses `localhost` and so tailscale tears down the DERP connection and recreates it.\r\n\r\nThe net result of all of this is that tailscale is constantly tearing down and recreating the DERP connections on both sides, so sometimes the connections never stay up long enough for our ping to get through.",
