    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "I think that, fundamentally, our method of disabling P2P is breaking Tailscale assumptions.  Namely: Tailscale assumes that we can send UDP to at least one STUN server, and if we can't then we are likely broken at the IP socket layer and need to rebind.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, our method of disabling P2P leaves the binding to UDP socket in place, meaning that workspaces have an open socket.  If you could somehow figure out the IP address of a workspace, you could send it Disco packets and it would happily set up a tailscale connection with you.  This all assumes you have the right crypto keys, which means you have to be an authorized user of the workspace and still go through the coordinator, but when customers ask us to disable P2P for security or compliance reasons, they probably won't be happy that we still have this open socket you can get in through.\r\n\r\n@deansheather @coadler I'd like your thoughts on the following\r\n\r\nOption 1\r\n=======\r\n\r\nA relatively limited tailscale fix would do something like spin through the DERP map, and if _every_ region has STUN disabled, then lie in the netcheck and say UDP is fine.  With no STUN servers at all, rebinding is just never going to do us any good.\r\n\r\nOption 2\r\n=======\r\n\r\nA more extensive tailscale fix would involve us adding a configuration option to directly tell tailscale not to bother with UDP binding & STUN at all.  We never open a UDP listening socket, and disable all STUN interactions.",
